<div id="review_310406030" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/310406030" />
    <a title="Terra" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/995356-terra"><img alt="Terra" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1512597861p2/995356.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/310406030?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Terra" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Terra" href="/user/show/995356-terra">Terra</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer310406030" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1054926686969328603">I grew up on small family farms, always having access to fresh and ultra local produce. There are baby photos of me chomping on home grown and delicious tomatoes and while my mother spent time tending the garden, I&apos;d spend time picking beans and tomatoes straight from the vine and eating them immediately. <br/><br/>As an adult, I&apos;ve maintained a small backyard garden, always with tomatoes, as they&apos;ve also been an easy crop for me to grow and tomato season is always my favorite. There is nothing like the f</span>
  <span id="freeText1054926686969328603" style="display:none">I grew up on small family farms, always having access to fresh and ultra local produce. There are baby photos of me chomping on home grown and delicious tomatoes and while my mother spent time tending the garden, I'd spend time picking beans and tomatoes straight from the vine and eating them immediately. <br /><br />As an adult, I've maintained a small backyard garden, always with tomatoes, as they've also been an easy crop for me to grow and tomato season is always my favorite. There is nothing like the flavor that comes with an actually fresh and recently vine ripened tomato and I've come to despise the crap tomatoes found in our supermarkets and reading Tomatoland only made me despise them even more. <br /><br />This book is eye opening, of course, and not only explains why supermarket tomatoes are so bland and gross, but also goes deeper into the tomato industry to examine, uncover and explain the awful human toll that goes into tomato production as well, facts that make me never, ever want to buy another grocery store tomato again. <br /><br />Tomatoland is redundant at times, with certain phrases recycled throughout the book and I wish it had ended with a call to action. I found the end a little disappointing, as I had hoped to reach the conclusion and find a "this is what you do to make things less awful in Tomatoland," but it's not there. <br /><br />All in all, it's an interesting and easy read, if a bit horrifying at times.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1054926686969328603" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


